Benita never learned to read until she was grown and never forgot what it cost to be spoken over, and so she does the work the intellectuals forget: she sits with the militant nobody quotes, the woman who runs the mimeograph and raises four children, the old comrade who has given forty years and one good coat. She reminds the leadership that a party is not its Central Committee but the people who keep coming back, and she keeps them coming back.
